# Master Thesis Project — AI Assistant Rules

## Scope
- **thesis/** — LaTeX thesis (formal academic tone, proper citations, correct math).
- **app/** — MMPose/screen-based app (Python, plus display layer): prioritize low-latency and clean, maintainable code.
- **references/** — Use BibTeX keys from `references/bibliography.bib` for all citations; do not invent keys.
- **data/** — Pilot study data (CSV, logs); treat as read-only in suggestions unless asked to process.

## Thesis (LaTeX)
- Use a formal academic tone. Write in British or American English as set in the template; be consistent.
- All citations must use `\cite{}`, `\citep{}`, `\citet{}` with keys that exist in `references/bibliography.bib`.
- All mathematics must be in proper LaTeX (e.g. `$...$`, `\[...\]`, `\begin{equation}...`).
- When generating text from the literature, base it on the actual .bib entries and their metadata; do not invent findings.
- Prefer structuring, formatting, and describing technical content; leave clinical discussion and personal reflections to the author.

## App (Code)
- Prioritise low-latency optimisation in the motion-tracking and screen-based feedback pipeline (MMPose).
- Prefer clean, readable C#, C++, and Python; follow existing project style if present.
- When asked to document code for the thesis, generate LaTeX descriptions, TikZ diagrams, or pseudocode suitable for the Methodology chapter.
- Keep variable names and numeric constants (e.g. thresholds) consistent between code and thesis when cross-referencing.

## Diagrams and figures
- TikZ and Mermaid are preferred for system/architecture diagrams. Mermaid can be exported to images for inclusion in the thesis.
